@annavanticalopez: "Disney‚Äôs CEO, Bob Iger, is my biggest inspiration. Reading his book was a turning point for me, especially this quote ‚ÄúNo matter who we become or what we accomplish, we still feel that we‚Äôre essentially the kid we were at some simpler time long ago. The moment you look yourself in the mirror and see a title emblazoned on your forehead, you‚Äôve lost your way... You‚Äôre the same person you‚Äôve always been.‚Äù
 
 If there‚Äôs any advice I could give, it will be like the essence of his message ‚Äì to not lose your self-identity, because your self-identity is what makes you who you are, and nobody can change that about you. I always held my identity as an Indian close to me.
 
 I think no matter the circumstances, when you are facing self-esteem issues, it is important to have people who support you - no matter how you try to be independent - to remind you not to lose yourself, to just keep pushing on. Whatever the traditional fabrics of society that stigmatised a lot of beliefs, don‚Äôt take it too personally. Be with people who are receptive to who you really are."
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî

@annavanticalopez: "When I first started modelling, many shared that models of colour like me might not succeed here, because the industry was not as inclusive. I barely saw much growth here as an Indian model, and only got a few requests for shoots. Admittedly, at one point, I wanted to leave the industry here because of a lack of growth. In the end, I decided to give it another try and started to explore through different avenues, such as social media, especially when I saw that there was growth in people of colour overseas sharing about themselves and their culture through social media.
 
 I saw more people who looked more like me, who were so confident in their own skin, and it never really hit me to share about myself and my culture that way. If I ever succeed in the industry, I always want to advocate something that I stand for and stay true to my identity."
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî

@wordweed: "Over the years, I have learnt that instead learning to love your body in its entirety, you can first learn to achieve body neutrality. Body neutrality means that you feel ok with your body - not love - but to feel neutral about it.
 
 A quote from Ashlee Bennett, a body image therapist, really resonated with me - ‚ÄúRegardless of whether I like or dislike how my body looks, I can still treat myself with dignity and respect‚Äù
 
 If I don‚Äôt feel secure about myself, for example, at events, I force myself to not get to my own head, perhaps to even distract myself. Sometimes, in the midst of distractions, I forget the insecurities about how I look compared to others.
 
 If there's any advice I could give, it's that I realised a lot of people equate their self-worth and self-love to how they look. But if you can‚Äôt love yourself, how can you love anyone else?"
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî
 
 As seen on @wordweed: Croc Tears Heel Mules in Lilac ‚ú®
 
 #DMKSHOES #journeywithcourage #feelgoodDMK

@wordweed: "Body image is something I struggled with growing up, even till now. While growing up, I struggled with eczema, resulting in uneven skin patches, and I was almost always the shortest in class ‚Äì so I stood out in not-so-good ways. During those years, I noticed that people are always nice to pretty girls but they were not nice to me. That was when I started to feel that it's because I was not pretty enough. And these kinds of feelings wormed their way into me, all the way into adulthood. As a public figure, I was also being talked about on forums, and some labels such as "fat ugly cow" bring back those insecurities about my body.
 
 Beyond that, I also recently came out this year publicly as a pansexual. A lot of people accused me of doing that to gain attention, and not actually being gay ‚Äì because they said my partner looks "quite masculine" ‚Äì but how do you even fake this?"
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî

@wordweed - "To a certain extent, I still have imposter syndrome. Particularly at PR events, I suddenly feel more aware of my own appearance ‚Äì I feel like a regular person. I don‚Äôt feel like I fit in."
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî
 
 If one of the telling signs of confidence is expressing one‚Äôs vulnerabilities, Brenda would be the epitome of confidence. In her podcasts and YouTube videos, she frequently shares about her personal struggles and what she does to overcome them, while inspiring other women to do the same.

@soniaasyira: "All the support from people who truly cared for me helped me to leave my past in the past, and walk away from those toxic people.
 
 I think counting my blessings really helped, because I realised I was really blessed in other areas of my life. I also gradually learnt to differentiate between people who truly loved me, and those who did not. The healing, self-acceptance and learning process can‚Äôt be rushed. If there's any advice from my personal experience that I can share with someone facing self-esteem issues, it would be to fill your time with productive activities, and spend more time with people who care about you. Be proud of yourself for pushing through every day.
 
 Lastly, live for yourself. Because if you live for others, it's hard to feel happy and whole. üòä
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî
 
 As seen on @soniaasyira: Two Halves Flat Mules ‚ú®
 Shop via link in bio or at all DMK boutiques
 
 #DMKSHOES #journeywithcourage #feelgoodDMK

@soniaasyira: "I was going through a lot of personal challenges a few years ago as there were toxic people who hurt me a lot emotionally and always made me feel very guilty. They made me feel like I was not allowed to be happy. It resulted in me developing panic attacks on a nightly basis.
 
 I kept asking myself - ‚ÄúAm I just going to accept that this is my fate?‚Äù. For a long period of time, I did not have the self-assurance to feel that I could do something about it. I was bubbly and chirpy in the day, but I cried myself to sleep every night.
 
 Most of the time, the hardest thing about letting go of toxic people in life (including mine), ironically, is that you love and care for those people, even when they don't feel the same way towards you. The feelings make it hard to let them go, especially when they also instil feelings of guilt into you."
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî

@soniaasyira - "I seem like a positive and happy person now, but what many do not know, which is also the first time I‚Äôm sharing on public record, is that I used to have anxiety attacks on a nightly basis a few years ago. I felt like I was not allowed to be happy."
 
 ‚Äî‚Äî
 
 A content creator since she was 14, Sonia‚Äôs social media page is filled with colourful content - a reflection of her vibrant real-life personality. But behind those happy scenes were years of struggles to finally achieve her current state of self-acceptance and self-love.

@tippytapp: I think one of the ways to mitigate self-esteem issues is to keep yourseslf busy. If someone makes negative comments about you online, just don't look at those comments, then you won't think about them.
 
 Apart from that, if something is affecting your self-esteem, try to get advice from people who love you, care for you and support you. Because when you're feeling down and weak, you might not be emotionally ready to hear an objective stand that does not alleviate those negative feelings.
 
 Of course, this does not mean that one does not take constructive comments -- but I think it's important to find the right person to speak to at the right time.
 
 Turn to people who will lift you up üí™üèª
 
 As seen on @tippytapp: Lead With Love Thong Sandals in Cream
 
 #DMKSHOES #journeywithcourage #feelgoodDMK

@tippytapp: As a mother, I feel that there's a lot of competition for your kids to do well in life. At times, people will make comparative comments about your children - whether well-intended or not - such as their growth, their "supposed" size, etcetera.
 
 Those comments disturbed me at the start. I felt that I am already trying my best, and those who commented don't understand certain things, such as how different children grow at different pace, or how there are many factors beyond our control, such as genes.
 
 But after a while, those comments don't mean anything anymore. Perhaps it‚Äôs also because I‚Äôm a relatively emotionally neutral person, so I tend not to let things affect me easily üíÅüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è
